## Diagnosis

I don't have access to your codebase or the files you just shipped, so I cannot make the changes directly. But I can give you the exact fix pattern and the root cause so you can resolve it completely.

---

## Root Cause

This is **CAP-016: LLM Typographic Defaults Override Voice Rules**.

Language models are trained on edited prose where em dashes are extremely common — house style at most publishers. Without an explicit constraint in the generation prompt or a lint gate in the pipeline, the model defaults to em dashes every time it needs a parenthetical pause, an interruption, or an appositive. Your voice rule exists in documentation, but it is not enforced at generation time or commit time, so it gets violated on every new content pass.

---

## Fix

### Step 1 — Find every em dash in the case study content

```bash
# The em dash character is U+2014
grep -rn "—" src/app/work/elan/
```

Also check your Payload seed data or MDX source:

```bash
grep -rn "—" src/payload/seed/
grep -rn "—" content/
```

### Step 2 — Decide the correct replacement for each instance

Your voice rule bans em dashes, so you must rewrite each one — not just swap characters. The replacement depends on context:

| Em dash use | Approved rewrite |
|---|---|
| Parenthetical aside | Rewrite as a separate sentence, or use commas |
| Before a list or elaboration | Use a colon |
| Interruption or pivot | Rewrite the sentence |
| Attribution in a pull quote | Use a simple hyphen-minus `-` or `—` → delete and reformat |

### Step 3 — Mechanical replacement as a safety net (after rewriting)

If any survive rewriting, a raw character swap is not enough — the prose will still read awkwardly. But for a quick audit pass:

```bash
# Dry run: show what would change
sed -n 's/—/[EM DASH FOUND]/gp' src/app/work/elan/page.tsx

# In-place replacement placeholder so nothing ships accidentally
# Replace with your chosen character/rewrite after reviewing
sed -i '' 's/—/--REWRITE-ME--/g' src/app/work/elan/page.tsx
```

### Step 4 — Add a lint rule so this never ships again

Create `.eslintrc` content or a standalone script. The simplest durable gate is a pre-commit hook:

```bash
# .husky/pre-commit  (add this line)
npx ts-node scripts/lint-voice.ts
```

```typescript
// scripts/lint-voice.ts
import { execSync } from "child_process";

const BANNED_CHARACTERS: Record<string, string> = {
  "\u2014": "em dash (—)",
  "\u2013": "en dash (–)",   // add if also banned
};

const SEARCH_PATHS = [
  "src/app/work/",
  "content/",
  "src/payload/seed/",
];

let violations = 0;

for (const [char, label] of Object.entries(BANNED_CHARACTERS)) {
  const escaped = char; // grep handles the raw character fine
  try {
    const result = execSync(
      `grep -rn "${char}" ${SEARCH_PATHS.join(" ")}`,
      { encoding: "utf8" }
    );
    if (result.trim()) {
      console.error(`\n[voice] Banned character found: ${label}`);
      console.error(result);
      violations++;
    }
  } catch {
    // grep exits 1 when no matches — that is the success case
  }
}

if (violations > 0) {
  console.error(`\n[voice] ${violations} voice violation(s). Fix before committing.`);
  process.exit(1);
}

console.log("[voice] No banned characters found.");
```

### Step 5 — Encode the rule in every generation prompt

If you are generating case study copy with an LLM, add this to your system prompt as a hard constraint — not a style note:

```
HARD RULE — TYPOGRAPHY:
Never use em dashes (—) or en dashes (–).
If you feel the urge to use one, rewrite the sentence.
Use a colon for elaboration, a period for separation, or commas for asides.
This is non-negotiable. Violation will require a full rewrite pass.
```

---

## Why This Keeps Happening

Three compounding failures, each of which would be sufficient on its own:

1. **No machine enforcement.** The rule lives in a document. Documents are not checked at commit time. Humans forget; models ignore.

2. **LLM typographic defaults.** Em dashes are statistically the model's preferred punctuation for sophisticated-sounding prose. Without an explicit, repeated prohibition in the prompt, it will always reach for them.

3. **No review checklist item.** If content review does not include a literal `grep -r "—"` step, the character slips through because readers process meaning, not individual Unicode code points.

---

## Principle

**Voice rules must be enforced by tooling, not memory.**

Any rule that requires a human to remember it at the right moment will eventually be broken. The pre-commit hook makes violation impossible to ship. The prompt constraint reduces violations at generation time. Together they close the loop.
